title: For Trade:  Marlin 30/30 "Texan"
postcontent: Up for possible trade is a Marlin 30/30 lever action, the model known as the "336 Texan". The rifle dates back to 1974, and is pre-Remington, pre-safety, with the JM stamp. Condition is "good", for a rifle that's over 40 years old and has clearly been used, with some visible wear and scuffs on the walnut stocks and a patch of light bluing wear on the upper barrel area, but it's nothing really major. Some folks might consider the stock a good canidate for a refinish job, but there are no cracks or major dings, so I just looked at it as a little honest wear, mostly some scuffs in the varnish on the buttstock that you can see in the pics. But overall it is solid and clean, mechanically and internally, with a crisp bore and crown.If you're reading this you already know these are particularly desirable and much less common than the standard 336's, so, no, I ain't selling it for $350 like any other 336.It has see-thru rings and a Tasco scope, but the scope is an early Japanese-made model, which were of considerably higher quality than later ones made in China (though even those seem to function just fine). The scope works great, and the glass is surprisingly clear for a budget scope, there's no need to replace it with another scope for a sub-200yd deer shot.I got this in a trade a while back with a local guy I've known for decades, it functions perfectly, and is dialed in. I'm not dying to get rid of it, I'm just bored and considering some new toy, you know how that goes.I don't really have any particular trade interests other than pistols chambered in 9mm or 38, but you never know, and I'll respond politely to any serious offer. Worst I can say is "no thanks".Trader must be legal to own firearms, and be a Georgia resident, over age 18. As always, I'll show my DL and Ga carry permit.Thanks for looking......
